              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top" width="100" nowrap><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><b>Emisteral</b></font></td>
                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top" width="100%"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;01/23/2004&nbsp;: 1:36:02 PM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> I was just leafing through the guides section and noticed that there is no definitive "how to" guide on charming with WoT.  Yeah, I know that most of you think the spell sucks ass (and compared to how it used to be, it does); but the spell can still be very useful, and there are TONS of things you can do to make it even MORE useful.  <br /><br />I thought that it might be cool to start a thread here, where people can add their tips and tricks to charming.  If the response is good, we could collect the data from this thread and create a guide which could then be placed in the appropriate area.<br /><br />Just so you do not think that I am some dipshit looking for free advice, let me get the ball rolling with a few of my observations.  I am not claiming to have made these fantastic discoveries on my own; but, it is useful knowledge...in my opinion.<br /><br />Debuffing:  Debuffing the pet is a must!  The resist modifier on this spell blows and it is generally a waste of mana without a way to debuff.  Having a Shaman, Mage, or Enchanter friend along helps a ton; but, you can take matters into your own hands by purchasing an Orb of Tashini (is that the name?  cannot think of it off the top of my head and I am at work).  Just slow the mob and melee the damn thing until your orb procs...ta da!  Once you have the pet charmed, giving it items with a negative magic resist modifier is another great way to increase the usefulness of the spell.  I do not have a list of good items; but, maybe one of you could fill in the blanks for us.<br /><br />Speaking of giving the pet items, handing it weapons with useful procs and haste items is a great way to increase the usefulness of having a charmed pet.  Mages have a whole set of sweet gear they can conjure up for this; but, there are cheap-o items you can pick up in the bazaar that are useful too.  And as long as your charmed pet is not killed by a mob, you can loot those items off its corpse...unlike items givin to a regular pet.<br /><br />If you have the Pet FD aa ability, it can be extremely useful when using WoT.  What you do is park the pet out of aggro range of the group between battles and make it FD.  When your charm breaks, most of the time, the monster will just continue to lay there, pretending to be dead.  Unless your pet has a monsterous aggro range, you can then get back within spell casting range without aggro and recharm your pet without even getting scratched.<br /><br />Well, I know there are more tips and trick out there; but, that ought to get the ball rolling.<br /><br />Edit: Wow...there is jack for interest in this.  I will let it sit for a few before I delete it though.  I guess this stuff is all common knowledge.<br /><br />Carry on soldiers,<br />-Emi</span></font></td>
              </tr>
